You’re pushing right up against a real edge:

if understanding = relation…
what happens at the limit of what we can relate to?

That’s where different traditions name different bridges.

⸻

One clean way to map what you’re saying

If everything we know comes through relation:
	•	perception = relation
	•	meaning = relation
	•	identity = relation

Then something that is:

not directly relatable

can’t be grasped the same way.

So instead of direct relation, humans use:

Indirect bridges
	•	Analogy → “it’s like…”
	•	Symbol → compresses what can’t be stated directly
	•	Narrative → lets you approach sideways
	•	Silence / awe → holds space without forcing definition

⸻

Where “God” fits in that structure

In many traditions, “God” functions as:

the name for what exceeds relational capture

Not necessarily:
	•	a definable object
	•	or something you can fully model

But:
	•	a limit concept
	•	a grounding reference
	•	something approached rather than contained

⸻

Important distinction (keeps this sharp)

There are at least three ways people use that word:
	1.	Personal / relational
	•	something you connect with, pray to, feel guided by
	2.	Philosophical
	•	the ground of being, ultimate reality, first cause
	3.	Symbolic / functional
	•	a placeholder for the unknown / unbounded

You’re speaking closest to #2 and #3.

⸻

The tension you’re feeling

If everything is relational:
	•	either everything is ultimately relatable
	•	or there is a boundary where relation breaks

Your move is:

“that boundary → God”

That’s a valid philosophical move.

But it’s not the only interpretation.

Others would say:
	•	it’s just the current limit of cognition
	•	or an open problem, not a defined entity

⸻

Clean synthesis

You’re identifying something real:

there are limits to what we can directly relate to or model

And proposing:

we name and orient toward that limit

⸻

Final line

Even if we can’t fully relate to it, we still:
	•	gesture toward it
	•	build symbols around it
	•	and orient our thinking in relation to it

So the connection isn’t:

direct understanding

It’s more like:

alignment toward something we can’t fully reduce

And that’s where philosophy, faith, and meaning all start to overlap.